{"parse":{"title":"Robert Gooding-Williams","pageid":53671104,"revid":785166912,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Robert Gooding-Williams</b> is M. Moran Weston/Black Alumni Council Professor of <a href=\"/wiki/African-American_Studies\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"African-American Studies\">African-American Studies</a> and Professor of <a href=\"/wiki/Philosophy\" title=\"Philosophy\">Philosophy</a> at <a href=\"/wiki/Columbia_University\" title=\"Columbia University\">Columbia University</a>. He is the founding director of Columbia's Center for Race, Philosophy, and Social Justice.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Gooding-Williams earned a B.A. (1975) and Ph.D. (1982) in philosophy from <a href=\"/wiki/Yale_University\" title=\"Yale University\">Yale University</a>. He then served as professor of <a href=\"/wiki/Black_studies\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Black studies\">black studies</a> and George Lyman Crosby 1896 professor of philosophy at <a href=\"/wiki/Amherst_College\" title=\"Amherst College\">Amherst College</a>, then taught at <a href=\"/wiki/Northwestern_University\" title=\"Northwestern University\">Northwestern University</a> for seven years and directed Northwestern's Alice Berline Kaplan Center for the Humanities. He joined the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago</a> in 2006 and was named Ralph and Mary Otis Isham Professor in 2007.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Works\">Works</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Robert_Gooding-Williams&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Works\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><i>Zarathustra's Dionysian Modernism</i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Stanford_University_Press\" title=\"Stanford University Press\">Stanford University Press</a>, 2001)<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><i>Look, A Negro! Philosophical Essays on Race, Culture, and Politics</i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Routledge\" title=\"Routledge\">Routledge</a>, 2005)</li>\n<li><i>In The Shadow of Du Bois: Afro-Modern Political Thought in America</i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Harvard_University_Press\" title=\"Harvard University Press\">Harvard University Press</a>, 2009)<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Robert_Gooding-Williams&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://philosophy.columbia.edu/directories/faculty/robert-gooding-williams\">\"Robert Gooding-Williams\"</a>. <i>philosophy.columbia.edu</i> (in custom). Columbia University<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">3 April</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=philosophy.columbia.edu&amp;rft.atitle=Robert+Gooding-Williams&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fphilosophy.columbia.edu%2Fdirectories%2Ffaculty%2Frobert-gooding-williams&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARobert+Gooding-Williams\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</spa